This is a simple desk sand for sticker backed Zink prints. The face measures 75mm x 50mm x 1mm and can be used in horizontal or vertical positions. Prints very quickly and is strong and stable.

I recently posted a similar strip in a stand. I wondered if could be printed without a stand and I've printed one without any significant problem.
IMPORTANT NOTE: I printed this at 2x design size.
I've posted 1 stl file with stabilising posts which are readily removeable after printing.
Printed in DiamondAge PLA on an Ultimaker 1.
Some of the photos show the item on the print plate (removed from the printer) before any finishing.

I used 210C, 0.2mm layer height, 1.2mm shell and 20% infill. No brim, raft or support. Most of the print was at a print speed of 50mm/s but I slowed this down substantially for the top third of the print.
As already noted I recommend printing this at 2x design size.
Naturally the underside of the centre of the bottom section and the apex are not of a high standard, but I think acceptable after some post printing clean up.
These regions might be improved by using support - I haven't tried.

description.text:
After reviewing the available parts on Thingiverse (of which there are many!) for laptop connector hubs, I decided to create a custom part for my own cables. The hardware this part is designed for is the Macbook Pro 15 inch retina (mid 2014). Ports included are: power supply, both Thunderbolt ports, USB, and headphone jack. I used a micrometer to measure the size of my current apple power supply terminal, and designed all cable terminal-hub interfaces to have a -0.2 mm fit (hub is smaller than cable terminal housing). USB and Thunderbolt terminal housings vary quite a bit in all dimensions, so there is a chance this may not fit your specific connectors.

Part is available at: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/a196b600e6f6e8c0ad7bfc9e/w/2082e1db4c7cc63f5996dca5/e/627410629d75fce8e1e79e2c

description.text:
UPDATE: I'm marking the Monster Kossel v1 as done.
I've printed a few hundred hours on it and proved it works as a printer reliably and with good precision. However the v2 is coming soon, and adds acrylic panels to make the printer enclosed, with the goal of fitting a HEPA and charcoal filter with a fan in aspiration on the top section, keeping the chamber in negative pressure. This is to placate my better half's concerns about health risks associated with lots of printing in a multi-purpose space.

These are the frame parts I modified from the original Kossel frame to work with the 2040 tower extrusions for a larger size.

The carriages are designed to snugly fit on the 20mm side when using original v-roller wheels from openbuilds.

The motor frames could use an additional tweak to allow for easier mounting of the NEMA 17 steppers in place, but that will be an upcoming edit. I increased the height of the bottom frame bits to get a more rigid feel between the tower and bottom frame.

UPDATE : just to make life easier for everyone, I want to point out that I'm still assembling this one. I've built a collection with all the parts I've printed that will go into this printer here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/goeland86/collections/monster-kossel - if you need additional bits you can use those as a reference instead of having to go hunting on your own for what works best. I posted the files before I was really ready because of a request on the Replicape slack team and found a whole lot of folks liked this design already... Thanks!

UPDATE : 29.06.17
I realized while assembling my Monster that the carriages I originally remixed wouldn't work when trying to put on the belts. I'm including a thicker version to enable you to use the original Kossel Mini carriages. I've also tightened the axles a bit to get a bit more of a snug fit on the 20x40 extrusion, as mine were loose with the genuine OpenBuilds V-Rollers.

IT PRINTS : 10.07.17
Finally! After a long time, I managed to pull of my first prints off the bed of the Monster Kossel yesterday. I'm using a Replicape board at the moment, with FSR bed leveling.
Some of you will have noticed that the steppers' lower screw holes can't be reached by a wrench... Sorry about that, but holding the motors in place with only two screws is working just fine for now, and the lever effect when the belts are tensioned mean the system is self-stabilizing as is, but I do plan on fixing those corners when I have a chance to. Oh that and also make some better cable management for those interested in mounting electronics on the top frame like I am. Pictures will come soon, I just want to make sure I clean up the mess of moving parts a bit... Final print volume looks to be around 320mm diameter by 440mm vertically, which is just what the doctor ordered.

UPDATE 30-sept-2017
So I still had some annoying wobble on the frame despite the use of the 20x40 extrusions for the towers. It was limiting the speed at which I could move and print. I fixed this by getting about 6.5 meters of 2mm steel wire to build cross bracing. Stick an M5x5mm screw on the top and bottom outside face of each OpenBuild extrusion and make one loop on the wire. Hook it to one screw and just go around the frame, up and down as required, and you should eventually come back to your starting point. Tension it gently by hand instead of going at it hard - too much tension will warp the frame out of square. Leave a little bit of margin upwards on the top screws, so you can tension by pulling the screws up, instead of re-sizing the cable. Works like a charm!

title: Prusa i3 MK2 Y carriage printable bed

description.text:
This is a fully printable Y carriage plate for mounting your heated bed. I adapted the Prusa i3 MK2 dxf file and modified it so that you can bolt on the arms in order to make this a fully printed part rather than having to rely on cutting one out of wood or having one laser cut or machined for you. It is 10mm thick, and the legs go in the slots only one direction each so that you cant mix them up and they use 3mm screws to bolt down. I printed mine with cubic infill to give it some additional rigidity, but it's a very solid piece once it's complete.

I adapted this version to use 4 lm8uu bearings instead of the 3 that are called for in the plans. However if you want to modify it back to a 3 bearing design, i'm including the sketchup file itself for your reference. I may improve this design by making it a little thinner so it's lighter. it comes in at about 159 grams. You can print this on a standard 200mm square build plate.

I also added additional 3mm holes for extra zip ties or screws for the bearings. Some of you like to use blocks so I gave plenty of options to tie them all down however you see fit.

May come back and add some lm8uu bearing brackets in the future if there is interes.

I used a top/bottom thickness of 1.5mm and a wall thickness of 2mm, but this is way overkill. you can use a 1mm thickness all around to speed up print time. as is, i printed it in about 8.5 hours.

Setting to 1mm wall/top/bottom thickness it drops to about 6.5 hour print at 60mm/sec.
use 8x m3x12 cap head or pan screws with nuts on the other side to attach the legs to the body. Legs mate to their slots in only one direction flush and tight.

Summary

Yet another power supply cover but with a place holder for solid state relay and XT60 connectors.

The original folger 2020 3D printer design has the supplied the power supply (S-260-12) hard wired to the power plug and whenever plugged in the extruder fan would be on. Also the power supply fan was running for no good reason. There is nothing wrong with this solution, I just like to make things more complicated. My goal was to only have the power supply only on during the print and cool down and controlled by the orange Pi (same as the raspberry Pi). The ramps / arduino is powered by the USB connector which allows you to remotely turn on and off the power supply via a 5V dc output. The output activates the solid state relay allowing 120VAC (could be 220VAC) to reach the power supply.

Parts

  • IEC Power connector. Most common and cost effective ebay and amazon. Link

  • Solid State relay (25A). Yes 25A is over kill but these are the cheapest solid state relays. Also works with only 3 VDC input if required. Link

  • XT60 connectors. These connectors should handle 60 Amps but my max load is about 15 A.

  • Power supply (S-260-12) Size (51 X 114 X 240) Provided from folger 2020 printer kit.

Wiring

If you are not comfortable handling the wiring of 120- 220 VAC then please do not do this project.

Ramps

On my ramps board, the header to control the relay is near the main power connectors. See picture. I connected the ps-on to the negative terminal of the relay and the Vcc connector to the positive terminal on the relay. The ps-on is grounded when on, as it was intended for an ATX power supply I believe.

Power Connector

Follow the picture for the suggested power connect connection on the back. Lastly, instead of connecting the brown wire to the power supply, connect it to the AC side of the replay and add a pigtail from the relay to the power supply.

Slicer Modifications

I had to modify the slicer start and end gcodes to turn the power on and off. I also added a cool down temperature to delay the turn of the power supply to allow the fans to cool the motors and extruder. Note I had to add the M19, M104, M109 codes as the slicer progam would put them before the power on (M80) code.

Start gcode
M80 ; turn on power supply
M190 S[first_layer_bed_temperature]
M104 S[first_layer_temperature]
G28 ; home all axes
G1 Z5 F5000 ; lift nozzle
M109; wait for temperature to reach

End gcode
M106 255 ; turn fan back on
M104 S0 ; turn off temperature
G28 X0 ; home X axis
M84 ; disable motors
M140 S20
M109 S100; wait for temperature to reach 100C
M140 S0; turn off temperature
M107 ; fans off
M81 ; turn off power supply

Firmware

The firmware must support the swtiching of the power switch. I am using Marlin firmware and had to add the below to the configuration.h and download to the arduino.
#define POWER_SUPPLY 1
Print took Approx. 2h

title: MakerFarm Pegasus E3D Titan + BLTouch Mount

description.text:
A mount designed for the MakerFarm pegasus metal mount. The mount will take a E3D Titan and a BLTouch.

Will not work with the new Aero (BLTouch would end up too low)

Resolution:

Notes:

Printed in ABS. I'm sure other filaments would work.

BLTouch Mounting

The BLTouch mounting requires heat set inserts, M3, short ones. I used the McMast-Carr 94180A331ones; 3.8mm long. The cannot be much longer then that as they will interfere with the stepper motor. The screws must also be quite short to not interfere with the motor. I used M3x8mm.
The BLTouch will likely need to be shimmed down slightly to be very close to 2mm above the nozzle. I found a piece of plastic 1.3mm thick and that brought me to about 1.8mm of the nozzle, plenty close enough. Basically assemble everything on the printer, figure out what size shim you need to get the BLTouch down to the right level, and cut it out and put it on.

Titan Mounting

There is nothing special to mounting the titan; the shorter screws should work fine, and the mount is the right thickness.

Make sure you put a nut in the capture on the mount before you bolt on the stepper, or you'll just end up taking it all apart again when you mount to the printer....

End-stop adjustment.

You will need to move the z-endstop both because of the bltouch and because this mount/extruder/hotend combo gives more print height.

You will need to move your X-endstop. If you do not reposition the bed, you will lose a tiny bit of build space in X because the nozzle position will not right the left most of the bed with the original bed position (with the supplied MakerFarm extruder).

Rebuilding Marlin.

You will almost certainly need to rebuild Marlin. I've added my Configuration.h for Marlin 1.1 to the files, but yours will likely be different (especially since my name is in there :) ) This is a whole topic on its own, but the enclosed one does work. It almost certainly could use some tweaking. The limits are set up for 8" pegasus with the bed in the original position.

Especially you'll need to adjust your extrusion steps/mm and enable auto-levelling.

title: Modular filament feeding system - extreme low profile

description.text:
NEW V3 revision

  • Click&snap mounting
  • Even more space for extruder travel in top Z position
  • Opened filament hole to easily push it out in case you brake it off
  • Added 6.30mm version for thicker frames, requested in comments.

V2 revision

  • Higher to avoid extruder collisions in top Z axis position
  • Added cable management holes, it should be possible to fit through smaller micro USB ports (bigger one don't fit), or standard 12V barrel connector for LED strips for example.
  • Overal slimmer profile
  • Improved unused filament holder, push in with pliers for best retainment.

Hey Thingiversers,

I would like to proudly introduce my newest and by far greatest upgrade for Prusa i3 MK2. As you can see in the photos, my shelf for 3D printer is indeed quite low and getting filament to the printer is quite tricky as I can't have spool holder on the frame, which I don't like much anyways. To date I was using different kind of filament guide which was box-2-extruder PTFE tube but when I would print something on max height in Z axis I would be grinding the PTFE tube along top of the shelf. So I came with this solution. It's not just super low profile it also allow for very easy grouping and getting almost as many materials ready to be easily swapped mid print or between prints as you can fit on the frame. I would suggest no more than 6 feeders at one time. Great feature is also integrated filament holder so it doesn't run away from you when not in use, just slide end of the filament in provided hole.

List of essentials:
Just get some PTFE tubes, this is very tight fit for 6/4mm tubes.
I get these from AliExpress cheap and good for this purpose.

If your are looking for other great upgrades, this one go perfectly with my IKEA Samla filament spool holder which can house 3 spools and feed all of it perfectly to the printer using this filament guide.

CAUTION: I have found out that the original design would cause collisions with extruder in top Z axis position. So if you print often high models with maximum Z axis position, get the new revised V2 version. If you need lower profile and will accept it's limits, then get the original design which is optimistically fine for Z axis up to 180mm but I wouldn't recommend stressing it too much thought.

Back to the machines and I would love to see your prints ;)

In case of questions let me know in the comments.

Happy printing!

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

Any will do

Notes:

This will print without supports as I have specifically designed supports for the cut out which can be easily removed with sharp knife post print. Otherwise it is designed the way it should perfectly bridge and not need any support material.

If you use Slic3r turn on "Detect thin walls" as it won't print these supports otherwise. If you use different slicer, just make sure in preview there are these supports generated. They are exactly 0.4mm so it should print just fine with 0.4 nozzle.

Note: To print right holder, just mirror the left holder in your slicer along Y axis.
Note2 - Slim version: To get slim version as you see the middle piece in photos, cut 3mm of each top and bottom in your slicer and print as usual. You should be able to do the same with left/right holders.

Remove custom supports

To save material and make support removal easier I have designed custom supports for the cut out, this is easily removed with sharp knife like box cutter or similar. Don't cut yourself, please. Be careful.

Optional: Skip this step if your PTFE tube feed through just fine.

Push PTFE tube in

It will be hard as the tolerance is 0, I wanted it to perfectly friction hold inside. In this case just get yourself flat screwdriver and gently push it in the cut out and push it apart, it shouldn't break as it is quite sturdy. Then push PTFE tube in, it will still go hard but will finally get through. Stop when it just slightly protrude from the other end - see photos.

Installation

Push assembled guide onto the frame. Connect other end of PTFE tube to whatever spool holder solution you have and feed filament through the tube and secure it in filament holder or feed it to your extruder.

description.text:
I created the propeller using the Onera HOR07 airfoil. All tests were performed on the Drone Propeller Thrust Tester You can inspect the results below.

Part printed at slow speed, with a 0.2mm extruder nozzle at 0.04 layer height. I deburred and cleaned the print using a Precision Knife

After this, it was sanded using a 400 grit sandpaper.

Here are the thrust measurements for some voltage presets (you can also view these in the images):

  • 1.5V => 12.54 grams
  • 2V => 17.31 grams
  • 2.5V => 22 grams
  • 3V => 40.17 grams

The included files consist of all shots taken during the test, with 6 text files that have all the airfoil coordinates used in the build, the STL files and finally the SLDPRT files. If you'd like to tinker with the propeller, make sure you have a few 8520 coreless motors.

You can use the SLDPRT extension files, should you desire to make your own changes to the drone propeller.

Note: Airfoil plotted by using the matplotlib library for python.

description.text: This is a design for a 3D printable set of drawers for organising small bits and pieces, such as electronics components. The design is parametric, so you can alter the size of cell of the grid, and you can also easily produce drawers that are a number of grid units high or wide. The latest version of the SCAD file is available here: https://github.com/tjhowse/printable_drawers

You'll need to print two matching frame_face pieces per cell you want. You'll also need to print two posts for every four-way intersection of cell corners, one for every two-way intersection of cell corners, such as on the edges of the stack, and one edge_post for every corner of the stack (usually 4). For example, for a simple 3x2 design as shown in my photo, you'll need ten post pieces, and four edge_post pieces, twelve frame_face pieces, and six drawer pieces.  
To assemble the drawers, lay half of the frame_face pieces down in your desired pattern. Now insert all of the post pieces. I recommend you use a piece of wood or a small hammer to get them seated properly. The SCAD file has an assembled() module that shows how the pieces fit. Once you've got all the posts in place you should not have any fins protruding from the edges of the drawers, and every drawer should have two rails supporting the lower left and right edges. Once all the posts are installed, lay the rest of the frame_face pieces on top and fit them onto the posts in the same orientation as the first set. Give each intersection a good tap down, turn it upright and insert your drawers. Done!

description.text:
I made this quick and easy mount for a Motorola Droid X. I have a few of these old phones and I use them as IP cams around my shop and property. I repeatedly use this particular one to watch my 3d printer and check if prints are going ok over my network. I was just propping it up on some junk to watch the bed, but a few weeks ago I made this mount for a pentax camera to do timelapse video of a print: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2288241 and I thought I may as well make a more permanent mount for the DX since I use it so much.

The initial design mounts the camera a bit too far off center, but I'm including it in case someone would rather use that design.

I just uploaded another design iteration, V3. I haven't printed it yet, but it should print with no issue. The only change was that I put a gusseted "ear" on the bottom of the mount to move the camera off center of my printer mount. The idea is that I will be able to turn the phone around and still be able to plug it in if I am going to leave it up and running for any length of time. If it doesn't work as planned I will update the design again soon.

This was an 8 bit violin created for a customer that was looking for a unique MIDI compatible violin.

This design was inspired by Ranjit's design, although was drawn from scratch by EVL to meet our design standards. The body top and sides were created from a single piece of basswood with a routed interior. Two options are available for the interior. One is for a more acoustic like tone, where the second roughed interior is designed to help minimize resonance, which is more important for compatibility with Pitch to MIDI converters.
The instrument body was routed inside, followed by the exterior shape being cut out. The f-holes were added to this piece as the last step. The maple back plate was cut out using a slightly different shape with the lower bout being wider than the rest of the body, allowing a ridge for a shoulder rest to attach. The neck is our standard 5 string neck, you can use a 4 string neck made using traditional techniques. The neck is attached using traditional techniques. The tailpiece and chin rest are also standard violin components. To make the instrument MIDI compatible a polyphonic pickup and preamp are necessary. In this instrument, EVL uses a specialized Barbera pickup and RMC preamp. The finish on this instrument is polyurethane, polished by hand to a high gloss.

description.text:
The Shapeoko2 shipped with an Altocraft spindle in December. On the stock spindle mount the rotary tool slams the top of the z-axis bracket reducing the ability to raise the carriage too high.  
This mount add-on pushes the tool out providing clearance at the top of the z-axis and also aligns the tool vertically with it's taper.

Initially printed at 20% infill and .3mm layer height to reduce prototyping print time.  Over tightening the bolts could cause crushing issues, so if printed for longer term use, I would print at least 90% infill.  
The top mount uses the bolts that came for the mount.   
The bottom mount uses M5x30mm bolts to mount it to the original aluminum mount.  
The bottom mount uses a capture nut and a M3x30mm bolt through the base for the cap. A shorter bolt could be used. Anything longer than 30mm will hit the back of the mount.  
** Depending on how deep you are milling into your work, you may need to adjust your z-axis rail assembly lower on the sub gantry to bring your tool closer to the MDF board. I was able to make this adjustment after everything was assembled.
